{{Italic title}}
{{Taxobox | name = ''Deinococcus geothermalis''
| image =
| image_caption =
| regnum = [[Bacterium|Bacteria]]
| phylum = [[Deinococcus-Thermus]]
| classis = [[Deinococci]]
| ordo = [[Deinococcales]]
| familia = [[Deinococcaceae]]
| genus = ''[[Deinococcus]]''
| species = '''''D. geothermalis'''''
| binomial = ''Deinococcus geothermalis''
| binomial_authority = Ferreira et al. 1997
}}

'''''Deinococcus geothermalis''''' is a bacterium. It produces orange-pigmented colonies and has an optimum growth temperature of about {{convert|45|°C|°F}} to {{convert|50|°C|°F}}. It is extremely [[gamma radiation]]-resistant. Its type strain is AG-3a (= DSM 11300).<ref name="FerreiraNobre1997">{{cite journal|last1=Ferreira|first1=A. C.|last2=Nobre|first2=M. F.|last3=Rainey|first3=F. A.|last4=Silva|first4=M. T.|last5=Wait|first5=R.|last6=Burghardt|first6=J.|last7=Chung|first7=A. P.|last8=Da Costa|first8=M. S.|title=Deinococcus geothermalis sp. nov. and Deinococcus murrayi sp. nov., Two Extremely Radiation-Resistant and Slightly Thermophilic Species from Hot Springs|journal=International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology|volume=47|issue=4|year=1997|pages=939–947|issn=0020-7713|doi=10.1099/00207713-47-4-939|pmid=9336890}}</ref>

A space mission called [[EXPOSE|EXPOSE-R2]] was launched on 24 July 2014 aboard the Russian [[Progress M-23M]],<ref name="Gronstal 2014">{{cite news |last=Gronstal |first=Aaron L. |url=http://phys.org/news/2014-07-exploring-mars-earth-orbit.html |title=Exploring Mars in low Earth orbit |work=NASA's Astrobiology Magazine |date=31 July 2014 |accessdate=2014-08-02 }}</ref> and was attached on 18 August 2014 outside the ISS on the Russian module [[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kramer |first=Miriam |url=http://www.space.com/26841-spacewalking-cosmonaut-launches-peru-satellite-video.html |title=Russian Cosmonaut Tosses Satellite for Peru During Spacewalk |work=Space.com |date=18 August 2014 |accessdate=2014-08-19 }}</ref> The two main experiments will test the resistance of a variety of [[extremophile]] microorganisms, including ''Deinococcus geothermalis'' to long-term exposure to outer space and to a Mars simulated environment.<ref>[http://meetingorganizer.copernicus.org/EPSC2013/EPSC2013-930.pdf BOSS on EXPOSE R2 Comparative Investigations on Biofilm and Planktonic cells of Deinococcus geothermalis as Mission Preparation Tests]. EPSC Abstracts. Vol. 8, EPSC2013-930, 2013. European Planetary Science Congress 2013.</ref>

==Genome structure==

''Deinococcus geothermalis'' has a genome that contains 2.47 Mbp with 2,335 protein coding genes. Additionally, it carries at least 2 [[plasmid]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last1 = Makarova | first1 = KS. | last2 = Omelchenko | first2 = MV. | last3 = Gaidamakova | first3 = EK. | last4 = Matrosova | first4 = VY. | last5 = Vasilenko | first5 = A. | last6 = Zhai | first6 = M. | last7 = Lapidus | first7 = A. | last8 = Copeland | first8 = A. | last9 = Kim | first9 = E. | last10 = Land | first10 = Miriam | last11 = Mavromatis | first11 = Konstantinos | last12 = Pitluck | first12 = Samuel | last13 = Richardson | first13 = Paul M. | last14 = Detter | first14 = Chris | last15 = Brettin | first15 = Thomas | last16 = Saunders | first16 = Elizabeth | last17 = Lai | first17 = Barry | last18 = Ravel | first18 = Bruce | last19 = Kemner | first19 = Kenneth M. | last20 = Wolf | first20 = Yuri I. | last21 = Sorokin | first21 = Alexander | last22 = Gerasimova | first22 = Anna V. | last23 = Gelfand | first23 = Mikhail S. | last24 = Fredrickson | first24 = James K. | last25 = Koonin | first25 = Eugene V. | last26 = Daly | first26 = Michael J. | title = Deinococcus geothermalis: the pool of extreme radiation resistance genes shrinks | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 2 | issue = 9 | pages = e955 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0000955 | pmid = 17895995 | pmc = 1978522 | display-authors = 8 | bibcode = 2007PLoSO...2..955M }} {{open access}}</ref>

