'''[[Scientific misconduct]]''' is the violation of the standard codes of [[scholarly method|scholarly conduct]] and [[ethics|ethical behavior]] in the publication of professional [[science|scientific research]]. A ''[[The Lancet|Lancet]]'' review on ''Handling of Scientific Misconduct in Scandinavian countries'' gave examples of policy definitions. In Denmark, scientific misconduct is defined as "intention[al] or gross negligence leading to fabrication of the scientific message or a false credit or emphasis given to a scientist", and in Sweden as "intention[al] distortion of the research process by fabrication of data, text, hypothesis, or methods from another researcher's manuscript form or publication; or distortion of the research process in other ways."<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Nylenna M, Andersen D, Dahlquist G, Sarvas M, Aakvaag A | title = Handling of scientific dishonesty in the Nordic countries. National Committees on Scientific Dishonesty in the Nordic Countries | journal = Lancet | volume = 354 | issue = 9172 | pages = 57–61 | date = July 1999 | pmid = 10406378 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(98)07133-5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Coping with fraud |work=The COPE Report 1999 |pages=11–18 |url=http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |quote=It is 10 years, to the month, since Stephen Lock ... |archive-date=2007-09-28 |access-date=2006-09-02|ref=COPE1999PDF}}</ref>
A 2009 [[systematic review]] and [[meta-analysis]] of survey data found that about 2% of scientists admitted to falsifying, fabricating, or modifying data at least once.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fanelli D | title = How many scientists fabricate and falsify research? A systematic review and meta-analysis of survey data | journal = PLOS One | volume = 4 | issue = 5 | page = e5738 | date = May 2009 | pmid = 19478950 | pmc = 2685008 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0005738 }}</ref> {{dynamic list}}
== Biomedical sciences == * Anna Ahimastos-Lamberti (Australia), a former medical researcher, admitted to fabricating scientific results published in numerous major international medical journals.<ref>{{cite web |title=High-profile researcher made up scientific results |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-17/high-profile-researcher-admits-to-fabricating-scientific-results/6781958 |website=ABC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en-AU |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> As a result, two journal articles about a three-year clinical trial involving a medication used to treat hypertension were retracted.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Nicky |title=Blood pressure research by scientist Anna Ahimastos retracted over faked data |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/blood-pressure-research-by-scientist-anna-ahimastos-retracted-over-faked-data-20150917-gjoqh0.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en |date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian scientist fabricated data |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-34275648 |website=BBC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> * [[Bharat Aggarwal]] (US), a former Ransom Horne, Jr. Distinguished Professor of Cancer Research at the [[University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center]],<ref>{{cite web | title = MD Anderson’s Bharat Aggarwal threatens to sue Retraction Watch |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2013/04/10/md-andersons-bharat-aggarwal-threatens-to-sue-retraction-watch/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-04-10|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> resigned his position after fraud was discovered in 65 papers published by him in the area of [[curcumin]] as a treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web | title = M.D. Anderson professor under fraud probe | url = http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/M-D-Anderson-professor-under-fraud-probe-3360037.phpV | work = Chiron }}</ref> Aggarwal has had 28 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cancer journals retract 10 papers, flag 8 more, and apologize for the delay |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/04/cancer-journals-retract-10-papers-flag-8-more-and-apologize-for-the-delay/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-04|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> * [[Elias Alsabti]] (Iraq, US), was a medical practitioner who posed as a biomedical researcher. He plagiarized as many as 60 papers in the field of cancer research, many with non-existent co-authors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Broad WJ | title = Would-be academician pirates papers | journal = Science | volume = 208 | issue = 4451 | pages = 1438–40 | date = June 1980 | pmid = 17796686 | doi = 10.1126/science.208.4451.1438 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woolf P | title = Fraud in science: how much, how serious? | journal = The Hastings Center Report | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 9–14 | date = October 1981 | pmid = 7309502 | doi = 10.2307/3561291 | jstor = 3561291 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=David | name-list-format = vanc |title=Research Fraud in the Behavioral and Biomedical Sciences|date=1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=978-0471520689|page=80|chapter=Plagiarism: The Case of Elias A.K. Alsbati}}</ref> * Piero Anversa (US, Italy) and [[Annarosa Leri]] (US, Italy), collaborators and former researchers at Harvard University, were found in a 2014 investigation to have "manipulated and falsified" data in their research on [[Endogenous cardiac stem cell|endogenous cardiac stem cells]], and to have included "false scientific information" in grant applications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Partners Healthcare and Brigham and Women’s Hospital Agree to Pay $10 Million to Resolve Research Fraud Allegations |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ma/pr/partners-healthcare-and-brigham-and-women-s-hospital-agree-pay-10-million-resolve|publisher=United States department of Justice|date=2017-04-27|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri lost a lawsuit they brought against Harvard that claimed the investigation had damaged their reputations.<ref>{{cite web | title = Judge dismisses cardiac stem cell researchers’ lawsuit against Harvard |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/29/judge-dismisses-cardiac-stem-cell-researchers-lawsuit-against-harvard/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri have one retracted and eight corrected publications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stem cell researchers investigated for misconduct recommended for roles at Italy’s NIH |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/14/stem-cell-researchers-investigated-for-misconduct-recommended-for-roles-at-italys-nih/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-14|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> In October 2018, Harvard University and Brigham and Women's Hospital called for an additional 31 paper retractions after many failed replications of their work.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/15/health/piero-anversa-fraud-retractions.html|title=Harvard Calls for Retraction of Dozens of Studies by Noted Cardiologist|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en}}</ref> * Edward Awh and graduate student David Anderson (US), formerly of the [[University of Oregon]], retracted nine of their publications due to data fabrication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2015/07/uo_grad_student_falsified_rese.html |title=Feds find UO grad student falsified research data, voiding results of four studies; The Oregonian |publisher=oreganlive.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2016/04/19/two-more-retractions-bring-total-to-9-for-neuroscience-duo/ |title=Two more retractions bring total to 9 for neuroscience duo; Retraction Watch |publisher=retractionwatch.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> This included an action identified by [[The Scientist (magazine)]] as a Top 10 Retraction of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/44895/title/The-Top-10-Retractions-of-2015/ |title=The Top 10 Retractions of 2015; The Scientist |publisher=the-scientist.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> * Werner Bezwoda (South Africa), formerly of the [[University of Witwatersrand]], admitted to scientific misconduct in trials on [[HDC/BMT|high-dose chemotherapy on breast cancer]], stating that he had "committed a serious breach of scientific honesty and integrity."<ref name=pmid10768448>{{cite journal | vauthors = Weiss RB, Rifkin RM, Stewart FM, Theriault RL, Williams LA, Herman AA, Beveridge RA | title = High-dose chemotherapy for high-risk primary breast cancer: an on-site review of the Bezwoda study | journal = Lancet | volume = 355 | issue = 9208 | pages = 999–1003 | date = March 2000 | pmid = 10768448 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(00)90024-2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Breast Cancer Researcher Admits Falsifying Data |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/05/us/breast-cancer-researcher-admits-falsifying-data.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2000-02-05|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Key Breast Cancer Study Was a Fraud |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/27/news/mn-56336|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=2001-04-27|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * Philippe Bois (US), a former postdoctoral fellow in biochemistry at [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]] was found by the [[United States Office of Research Integrity|Office of Research Integrity]] to have used misleading data for one image in a 2005 ''[[Journal of Cell Biology]]'' paper and completely faked another image in a ''[[Molecular and Cellular Biology]]'' article published the same year. The JCB paper was retracted later in May 2007 and the MCB paper was corrected.<ref>{{cite web | title = St. Jude postdoc faked images: A former postdoctoral researcher at St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital fudged images published in two papers, one of which has since been retracted.|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/st-jude-postdoc-faked-images-42317/|publisher=The Scientist|date=2011-06-22|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref> * [[Joachim Boldt]] (Germany), an anesthesiologist formerly based at the [[Justus Liebig University Giessen]], was stripped of his professorship and criminally investigated for forgery in his research studies.<ref>Heidi Blake, Holly Watt and Robert Winnett. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/8360667/Millions-of-surgery-patients-at-risk-in-drug-research-fraud-scandal.html "Millions of surgery patients at risk in drug research fraud scandal"]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 03 Mar 2011 (retrieved 2011-03-03)</ref> Boldt has had 96 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = When you have 94 retractions, what’s two more? |url=https://retractionwatch.com/category/joachim-boldt-retractions/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-03-01|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * C. David Bridges (US), a researcher at [[Purdue University]] and formerly at [[Baylor College of Medicine]], was found by a [[NIH]] investigation panel to have stolen ideas from a rival's manuscript that Bridges had been asked to review, and used that information to produce and publish his own research.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1989/07/13/nih-accuses-biologist-of-stealing-ideas-from-rival-researcher/fd8a3122-c461-49d8-bd05-c8b99e930f2d/|title=NIH Accuses Biologist of Stealing Ideas From Rival Researcher|publisher=The Washington Post|date=1989-07-13|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-07-17/local/me-2884_1_scientific-fraud|title=Journal Admits Fraud Fears|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1989-07-17|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The investigating panel described Bridges' conduct as "an egregious misconduct of science that undermines the entire concept and practice of scientific experimentation and ethical responsibility,"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/12/us/question-of-scientific-fakery-is-raised-in-inquiry.html|title=Question of scientific fakery is raised in inquiry|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1989-07-12|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> with NIH later stripping Bridges' of his funding.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|title=NIH panel strips researcher of funding after plagiarism review|journal=Chemical & Engineering News|volume=67|issue=32|page=24|publisher=American Chemical Society|date=1989-08-07|access-date=2018-04-18|doi=10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|last1=Zurer|first1=Pamela S}}</ref> * [[Silvia Bulfone-Paus]] (Germany, UK), an immunologist at the [[Research Center Borstel]] and the [[University of Manchester]], has had 13 of her publications retracted following investigations of alleged scientific misconduct involving image manipulation.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/news.2010.671 |title=German research centre widens misconduct probe |journal=Nature |year=2010 |last1=Schiermeier |first1=Quirin | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marcus|first=Adam | name-list-format = vanc |title=Bulfone-Paus retraction count grows to 13 with one in Transplantation|url=http://retractionwatch.wordpress.com/2011/12/13/bulfone-paus-retraction-count-grows-to-13-with-one-in-transplantation/|work=Retraction Watch|publisher=Retraction Watch|access-date=17 January 2012}}</ref> * [[Ranjit Chandra]] (Canada), former nutrition researcher at [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] and self-proclaimed "father of nutritional immunology,"<ref>{{cite web | title = Who is Ranjit Kumar Chandra? A timeline of notoriety | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/07/26/who-is-ranjit-kumar-chandra-a-timeline-of-notoriety/|date=2016-07-26|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> was in 2015 stripped of his [[Order of Canada]] membership following accusations of scientific wrongdoing in his research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disgraced researcher Ranjit Chandra stripped of 1989 Order of Canada|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/disgraced-researcher-ranjit-chandra-stripped-of-1989-order-of-canada/article28084791/|access-date=9 January 2016}}</ref> In 2015 Chandra lost a $132 million case against the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], which in 2006 presented a documentary in which 10 of Chandra's publications were identified as “fraudulent or highly suspicious;”<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher Chandra loses libel case against CBC |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/31/nutrition-researcher-chandra-loses-libel-case-against-cbc/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-31|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Chandra was ordered to pay the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] $1.6 million to cover the defendant's legal fees.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ranjit Chandra ordered to pay $1.6M to cover CBC's legal fees in libel lawsuit |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/chandra-paying-legal-fees-1.3322284|publisher=CBC/Radio Canada|date=2015-11-17|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> At least four of Chandra's publications have been retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher loses two more papers after misconduct findings come to light | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/06/16/nutrition-researcher-loses-two-more-papers-after-misconduct-findings-come-to-light/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-06-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * [[Ching-Shih Chen]] (US), the former chair of cancer research at [[The Ohio State University]], was investigated by OSU and the federal Office of Research Integrity after being anonymously reported for falsifying data. The investigation found that he falsified information in at least 11 publications, and that he did not keep any laboratory notebooks on his research, a violation of federal research policies.<ref>{{cite web|title=OSU Professor Falsified Data on Eight Papers, Resigns|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/52212/title/OSU-Professor-Falsified-Data-on-Eight-Papers--Resigns/|website=The Scientist}}</ref><ref name=lantern>{{cite web|title=Ohio State researcher forced to resign after falsifying data in cancer research projects paid for in part by Pelotonia and Stefanie Spielman cancer fund|url=https://www.thelantern.com/2018/03/ohio-state-researcher-forced-to-resign-after-falsifying-data-in-cancer-research-projects-paid-for-in-part-by-pelotonia-and-stefanie-spielman-cancer-fund/|website=The Lantern}}</ref> * [[Carlo M. Croce]] (US), an oncologist and professor of medicine at [[Ohio State University]], has been the subject of several allegations of scientific misconduct, including data falsification, and related institutional investigations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Years of Ethics Charges, but Star Cancer Researcher Gets a Pass|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/08/science/cancer-carlo-croce.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2017-03-08|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why The Ohio State University decided to go public about misconduct|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/04/why-ohio-state-university-decided-go-public-about-misconduct|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|date=2018-04-05|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Carlo Croce, facing misconduct allegations, accuses former colleague of misconduct|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/11/09/carlo-croce-facing-misconduct-allegations-accuses-former-colleague-misconduct/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-11-09|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> Croce, who has filed lawsuits against critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cancer Researcher Calls NY Times Profile Defamatory|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/cancer-researcher-says-ny-times-profile-defamatory/|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=2017-05-11|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> including a defamation lawsuit against [[David Sanders (biologist)]] of [[Purdue University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Croce v. Sanders|url=https://www.pacermonitor.com/public/case/21205255/Croce_v_Sanders|publisher=PacerMonitor LLC|date=2017-04-20|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> and a defamation claim against [[The New York Times]] that in 2018 was largely dismissed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge Tosses Researcher’s Libel Claims Against NY Times|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-tosses-researchers-libel-claims-against-ny-times/|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=2018-11-07|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> has had eight of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Probe into Carlo Croce reached "defensible and reasonable" decisions, says external review|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/05/probe-into-carlo-croce-reached-defensible-and-reasonable-decisions-says-external-review/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-05|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> * [[John Darsee]] (US), a cardiologist formerly based at [[Harvard University]], fabricated data in published research articles and more than 100 abstracts and book chapters.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stewart WW, Feder N | title = The integrity of the scientific literature | journal = Nature | volume = 325 | issue = 6101 | pages = 207–14 | year = 1987 | pmid = 3808019 | doi = 10.1038/325207a0 | bibcode = 1987Natur.325..207S }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Harvard Suspends Doctor For Fraud |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/16/us/harvard-suspends-doctor-for-fraud.html |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-12-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> In 1983 Darsee was disbarred for ten years by the US [[National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{cite web | title = U.S. to Penalize Heart Researcher on Fraudulent Project at Harvard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/16/us/us-to-penalize-heart-researcher-on-fraudulent-project-at-harvard.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1983-02-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Darsee has had at least 17 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/06/16/who-has-the-most-retractions-introducing-the-retraction-watch-leaderboard/ |title=Who has the most retractions? Introducing the Retraction Watch leaderboard |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-06-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * [[Dipak Das]] (US), former director of the Cardiovascular Research Center at the [[University of Connecticut Health Center]], was found in a University investigation to be guilty of 145 counts of fabrication or falsification of research data.<ref>[http://chronicle.com/blogs/percolator/uconn-investigation-finds-that-health-researcher-fabricated-data/28291 UConn Investigation Finds That Health Researcher Fabricated Data] ([[The Chronicle of Higher Education]], January 11, 2012)</ref> Das has had 20 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Late resveratrol researcher Dipak Das up to 20 retractions |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2014/03/27/late-resveratrol-researcher-dipak-das-up-to-20-retractions/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2014-03-27|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * Evan B. Dreyer (US), former Associate Professor of Ophthalmology at [[Harvard University Medical School]], reported falsified and/or fabricated experimental results in manuscripts and grant applications. In 2000 Dreyer was blocked for 10 years from receiving NIH-sponsored research grants.<ref>{{cite web | title = Findings of Scientific Misconduct |url=https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-01-006.html|publisher=NIH|date=2000-11-29|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2000/11/prof_accepts_penalty_for_past_misconduct |title=Prof accepts penalty for past misconduct |publisher=The Daily Pennsylvanian Inc.|date=2000-11-28|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = RSNA Journals Use Software to Fight Plagiarism |url=http://www.rsna.org/newsdetail.aspx?id=8570|publisher=Radiological Society of North America|date=2013-03-01|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> * [[Richard Eastell]] (UK), a medical doctor and Professor at the [[University of Sheffield]], was found in a 2009 [[General Medical Council]] hearing to be negligent in making "untrue" and "misleading" declarations involving a trial of the osteoporosis drug [[Actonel]].<ref>Phil Baty, [http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=409013&c=2 "Academic made ‘untrue’ declaration about ‘full access’ to research material, GMC finds"], ''Times Higher Education'', 10 November 2009</ref> Eastell had in 2006 resigned as director of research at Sheffield [[National Health Service]] Trust following allegations of "financial irregularities" connected to his research program.<ref>{{cite news |title=Doctor in drug research row quits NHS post |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/15/health.healthandwellbeing |date=2006-01-15 |author=Jo Revill |publisher=Observer |access-date=2009-09-08 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Drugs trial row scientist resigns |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=200608 |date=2006-01-06 |author=Phil Baty |publisher=[[Times Higher Education]] |quote=did not indicate that initial inquiries uncovered wrongdoing |access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejabberwock.org/wiki/index.php?title=Actonel_Case_Media_Reports |title=Actonel Case Media Reports – Scientific Misconduct Wiki |publisher=Thejabberwock.org |date=2011-07-07 |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> * [[Masoumeh Ebtekar]] (Iran), head of the [[Department of Environment (Iran)|Iranian Department of Environment]] at [[Tarbiat Modares University]] in Tehran, substantially plagiarized several previously-published articles in a 2006 paper that was later retracted.<ref name="eTBLAST">{{cite web |url=http://spore.swmed.edu/dejavu/duplicate/9866/ |title=Entry 9866 information &#124; Deja vu > Browse |publisher=Spore.swmed.edu |date= |access-date=2008-11-18 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Butler D | title = Iranian paper sparks sense of déjà vu | journal = Nature | volume = 455 | issue = 7216 | page = 1019 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18948918 | doi = 10.1038/4551019a }}</ref> * [[Terry Elton]] (US), Professor of Pharmacology at [[Ohio State University]], was found guilty of scientific misconduct by both a University committee and the [[Office of Research Integrity]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dahlberg|first=John | name-list-format = vanc |title=Findings of Research Misconduct|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2012-12-26/html/2012-30866.htm|publisher=Department of Health and Human Services|access-date=15 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Al-Ruwaishan|first=Abdulrahman|name-list-format=vanc|title=Ohio State pharmacy professor tampered with research data, hit with ‘severe’ federal sanctions|url=http://www.thelantern.com/campus/ohio-state-pharmacy-professor-tampered-with-research-data-hit-with-severe-federal-sanctions-1.2970128|access-date=15 January 2013|newspaper=The Lantern|date=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111012152/http://www.thelantern.com/campus/ohio-state-pharmacy-professor-tampered-with-research-data-hit-with-severe-federal-sanctions-1.2970128|archive-date=2013-01-11|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Elton has had seven of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2016/08/24/7th-retraction-for-ohio-researcher-who-manipulated-dozens-of-figures/ |title=7th retraction for Ohio researcher who manipulated dozens of figures |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-08-24|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * [[Yoshitaka Fujii]] (Japan), an anesthesiologist, was found to have fabricated data in at least 183 scientific papers, setting what is believed to be a record for the number of papers by a single author requiring retractions. A committee reviewing 212 papers published by Fujii over a span of 20 years found that 126 were entirely fabricated, with no scientific work done. Only 3 were found to be valid. He was also found to have forged the signatures of scientists he listed as co-authors without their knowledge.<ref name=ScienceInsiderNewRecord>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2012/04/new-record-retractions |title=A New Record for Retractions? |first=Dennis |last=Normile | name-list-format = vanc |work=Science |date=April 11, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Statement of Concern |author=S. Shafer |url=http://publicationethics.org/files/u7140/FujiiStatementOfConcern.pdf |format=PDF |year=2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/05/17/what-took-more-than-five-years-elsevier-retracts-20-papers-by-worlds-most-prolific-fraudster/|title=What took more than five years? Elsevier retracts 20 papers by world’s most prolific fraudster |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-05-17|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref> * Roxana Gonzalez (US), former doctoral student in the laboratory of [[Jennifer Lerner]] at [[Carnegie Mellon University]], falsified data in research projects supported by the US [[National Institutes of Health]] that "affected three published papers, two manuscripts, and one review article."<ref>{{cite web|author=ORI – The Office of Research Integrity |url=http://ori.dhhs.gov/misconduct/cases/Gonzalez.shtml |title=Case Summaries |publisher=Ori.dhhs.gov |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100215193840/http://ori.dhhs.gov/documents/annual_reports/ori_annual_report_2008.pdf "Office of Research Integrity – 2008 Annual Report"] (PDF) ori.dhhs.gov. p. 54 (pdf p. 62 of 84) Retrieved 20 December 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.the-scientist.com/blog/print/54912/ Grad student falsified data], [[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]], 5 August 2008.</ref> * [[Dong-Pyou Han]] (US), former assistant professor of biomedical sciences at [[Iowa State University]], added human antibodies to samples of rabbit blood in an effort to falsely enhance the utility of an experimental HIV vaccine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-isu scientist pleads guilty of AIDS vaccine fraud |author=Tony Leys |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2015/02/25/dong-pyou-han-iowa-state-university-guilty-plea/23996449/ |newspaper=[[The Des Moines Register]] |date=February 25, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2015/07/01/researcher-who-spiked-rabbit-blood-to-fake-hiv-vaccine-results-slapped-with-rare-prison-sentence/ |title=Researcher who spiked rabbit blood to fake HIV vaccine results slapped with rare prison sentence |publisher=The Washington Post|date=2015-07-01|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> In 2015 Han was sentenced to nearly five years in prison and ordered to return $7.2 million to the [[National Institutes of Health|NIH]].<ref>http://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/01/aids-vaccine-fraudster-sentenced-to-nearly-5-years-in-prison-and-pay-back-7-million/</ref> * [[Marc Hauser]] (US), an evolutionary biologist and former Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]], was found by a University committee and the US [[Office of Research Integrity]] to have fabricated and falsified data in his research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2010/08/harvard-dean-confirms-misconduct-hauser-investigation |title=Harvard Dean Confirms Misconduct in Hauser Investigation |work=Science |date=August 20, 2010 }}</ref><ref name="crimson20100914">{{Cite news |title = Marc Hauser's Fall From Grace |url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2010/9/14/hauser-lab-research-professor/ |newspaper = [[The Harvard Crimson]] |date = September 14, 2010 |access-date = October 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref name="Boston-Globe">Johnson, C., 2012. [https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/science/2012/09/05/harvard-professor-who-resigned-fabricated-manipulated-data-says/6gDVkzPNxv1ZDkh4wVnKhO/story.html Former Harvard professor Marc Hauser fabricated, manipulated data, US says] ''Boston Globe'' [