a former Professor in the Department of Medicine at the [[University of Vermont]], was convicted in 2005 of grant fraud after falsifying data in as many as 17 grant applications between 1992 and 2000. He was the first academic in the United States to be jailed for falsifying data in a grant application.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/22/magazine/22sciencefraud.html |author=Jeneen Interlandi |title=An Unwelcome Discovery |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2006-10-22 |access-date=2012-11-29 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Case Summary - Eric T. Poehlman |url=https://ori.hhs.gov/poehlman_notice|publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services Office of Research Integrity|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Poehlman has had seven of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = 12 years after researcher found guilty of misconduct, journal retracts paper | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2017/06/21/12-years-researcher-found-guilty-misconduct-journal-retracts-paper/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-06-21|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> * [[Anil Potti]] (US), a former Associate Professor of Medicine at [[Duke University]], engaged in scientific misconduct "by including false research data in ... published papers, [a] submitted manuscript, [a] grant application, and the research record."<ref>{{cite web | title = Findings of Research Misconduct | url = https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2015/11/09/2015-28437/findings-of-research-misconduct|publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services Office of Research Integrity|date=2015-11-09|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.wordpress.com/2012/02/22/tenth-potti-retraction-appears-in-clinical-cancer-research/ |title=Tenth Potti retraction appears, in Clinical Cancer Research &#124; Retraction Watch |publisher=Retractionwatch.wordpress.com |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> Potti's misconduct resulted in the suspension of three clinical trials based on his research and a lawsuit filed against Duke by patients enrolled in those studies.<ref>{{cite web | first = Jocelyn | last = Kaiser | name-list-format = vanc | title = Potti found guilty of research misconduct |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/11/potti-found-guilty-research-misconduct|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|date=2015-11-09|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Potti has had 11 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Anil Potti retraction record so far | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2012/02/14/the-anil-potti-retraction-record-so-far/ |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2012-02-14|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> * Azza El-Remessy (US), a former Associate Professor of the University of Georgia College of Pharmacy, falsified Western blot data in published manuscripts.<ref>{{cite web | title = Case Summary: El-Remessy, Azza | url = https://ori.hhs.gov/content/case-summary-el-remessy-azza | publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Findings of Research Misconduct, Notice Number: NOT-OD-18-006 | url=https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-18-006.html|publisher=National Institutes of Health|date=2017-10-12|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> * [[Scott Reuben]] (US), a former Professor of Anesthesiology at [[Tufts University]], falsified and fabricated clinical trials involving painkiller medications.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123672510903888207?mod=googlenews_wsj | title = Top Pain Scientist Fabricated Data in Studies, Hospital Says | work = [[Wall Street Journal]] | date = 11 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = A Medical Madoff: Anesthesiologist Faked Data in 21 Studies | url = https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/a-medical-madoff-anesthestesiologist-faked-data/|publisher=Scientific American|date=2009-03-10|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Reuben pleaded guilty in 2010 to one count of health care fraud and was sentenced to six months in prison.<ref>{{cite web | first = Jim | last = Edwards | name-list-format = vanc | title = Doc Who Faked Pfizer Studies Gets 6 Months in Prison, Showing Why Gift Bans Are a Good Idea |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/doc-who-faked-pfizer-studies-gets-6-months-in-prison-showing-why-gift-bans-are-a-good-idea/|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|date=2010-06-25|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> Reuben has had 25 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/category/by-author/scott-reuben-retractions/ |title=Scott Reuben notches 25th retraction, for a letter to the editor |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-11-23|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> * José Román-Gómez (Spain), a leukemia researcher at the [[University of Córdoba (Spain)]] who has been described as "a serial image manipulator/misappropriator," altered and misappropriated gel images from the work of others for his own published papers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloodjournal.hematologylibrary.org/content/early/2012/08/15/blood-2012-08-450304.full?sid=8c23befd-8112-416a-bec2-ca506425d10c |title=RETRACTION: Román-Gómez J, Cordeu L, Agirre X, Jiménez-Velasco A, San José-Eneriz E, Garate L, Calasanz MJ, Heiniger A, Torres A, Prosper F. Epigenetic regulation of Wnt-signaling pathway in acute lymphoblastic leukemia. Blood. 2007;109(8):3462-3469 |publisher=Bloodjournal.hematologylibrary.org |date=2012-08-16 |access-date=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloodjournal.hematologylibrary.org/content/113/10/2370.2.short |title=Roman-Gomez J, Jiminez-Velasco A, Castillejo JA, Agirre X, Barrios M, Navarro G, Molina FJ, Calasanz MJ, Prosper F, Heiniger A, Torres A. Promoter hypermethylation of cancer-related genes: a strong independent prognostic factor in acute lymphoblastic leukemia. Blood. 2004;104:2492-2498 |publisher=Bloodjournal.hematologylibrary.org |date=2009-03-05 |access-date=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Lifted figure prompts retraction of Oncogene paper by Roman-Gomez | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2013/02/08/lifted-figure-prompts-retraction-of-oncogene-paper-by-roman-gomez/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-02-08|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = JCO expresses concern over images from Spanish group that had aroused earlier concern |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2012/04/05/jco-expresses-concern-over-western-blots-from-spanish-group-that-had-aroused-earlier-concern/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2012-04-05|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Román-Gómez has had six of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Sixth Retraction for Leukemia Researcher | first = Andrew S. | last = Wiecek | name-list-format = vanc | url = https://www.biotechniques.com/news/340546|publisher=BioTechniques | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180330075950/https://www.biotechniques.com/news/340546 | archive-date = 30 March 2018 |date=2013-03-05|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[Steven S. Rosenfeld]] (US), a former Harvard undergraduate, forged [[letters of recommendation]] for himself in the name of David Dressler, whose laboratory he used. His research on [[transfer factor]], on which two articles were published in the ''[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]]'', could not be successfully replicated by other scientists. * Robert Ryan (UK), formerly of the [[University of Dundee]], was found by a University committee in 2016 to have committed research misconduct in his work on molecular bacteriology.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Dundee scientist resigns after research misconduct | url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/education/university-of-dundee-scientist-resigns-after-research-misconduct-1-4334327 | work = The Scotsman | publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd.|date=2017-01-08|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> Four of Ryan's publications have been retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Caught Our Notice: Former rising star loses fourth paper | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/21/caught-our-notice-former-rising-star-loses-fourth-paper/ |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-21|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * Fazlul Sarkar (US), a pathologist formerly at [[Wayne State University]], was in 2015 found by a University committee to have "engaged in and permitted (and tacitly encouraged) intentional and knowing fabrication, falsification, and/or plagiarism of data, and its publication in journals, and its use to support his federal grant applications."<ref>{{cite web | title = Investigation Finds Pathologist Guilty of Systemic Misconduct | url = https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/47297/title/Investigation-Finds-Pathologist-Guilty-of-Systemic-Misconduct/|publisher=The Scientist|date=2016-10-09|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> Sarkar, who in 2016 lost a defamation lawsuit he brought against anonymous critics of his work,<ref>{{cite web | title = PubPeer wins appeal of court ruling to unmask commenters | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/12/07/pubpeer-wins-appeal-court-ruling-unmask-commenters/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-12-07|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> has had 33 of his publications retracted, and at least a dozen others corrected.<ref>{{cite web | title = Researcher who once tried to sue critics has another dozen papers retracted | url =https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/17/researcher-who-once-tried-to-sue-critics-has-another-dozen-papers-retracted/#more-71450|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-17|access-date=2018-09-18}}</ref> * Yoshihiro Sato (Japan), a researcher in [[osteoporosis]] at Mitate Hospital in [[Tagawa, Fukuoka|Tagawa]], published more than 200 papers involving 33 clinical trials, of which 30 trials have been retracted (as of August 2018) either by Sato or by the journals.<ref>http://science.sciencemag.org/content/361/6403/636</ref> * Eric J. Smart (US), a former nutrition researcher, associate professor, vice-chairman of the Department of Pediatrics and the Barnstable-Brown Chair in Diabetes Research at the [[University of Kentucky]], was in 2012 found by the US [[Office of Research Integrity]] to have committed scientific misconduct over a period of 10 years by falsifying data in 10 published papers and seven grant applications.<ref>{{cite news |title=University of Kentucky researcher accused of falsifying data for a decade |author=Linda B. Blackford |url=http://www.kentucky.com/2012/11/26/2422095/university-of-kentucky-researcher.html#storylink=cpy |newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |date=2012-11-26 |access-date=2012-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Federal Register]] |volume=77 |number=224 |date=2012-11-20 |title=Findings of Research Misconduct |url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2012-11-20/html/2012-28209.htm |access-date=2012-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = ORI sanctions former University of Kentucky nutrition researcher for faking dozens of images in 10 papers |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2012/11/20/ori-sanctions-university-of-kentucky-nutrition-researcher-for-faking-dozens-of-images-in-10-papers/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2012-11-20|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Smart has had eight of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Two more Eric Smart retractions appear | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2013/04/16/two-more-eric-smart-retractions-appear/#more-13715|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-04-16|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * Alfred Steinschneider (US), a medical doctor formerly based at [[Upstate Medical University]], in 1972 developed the theory, published in the journal [[Pediatrics (journal)]], that [[Sudden infant death syndrome|SIDS]] was caused by prolonged [[Sleep apnea]],<ref name="aappublications646">{{cite journal | vauthors = Steinschneider A | title = Prolonged apnea and the sudden infant death syndrome: clinical and laboratory observations | journal = [[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]] | volume = 50 | issue = 4 | pages = 646–54 | date = October 1972 | pmid = 4342142 | url = http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/50/4/646 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Steinschneider A |title=Erratum? Prolonged apnea and the sudden infant death syndrome: clinical and laboratory observations |journal=[[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]] |volume=93 |issue=6 |page=944 |date=June 1994 |pmid= |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/93/6/944}}</ref> although none of his research or research conducted subsequently by others supported the theory.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hick JF | title = Sudden infant death syndrome and child abuse | journal = [[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]] | volume = 52 | issue = 1 | pages = 147–48 | date = July 1973 | pmid = 4724436 | url = http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/52/1/147 }}</ref><ref name="amazon1997">{{cite book |author1=Talan, Jamie |author2=Firstman, Richard |title=The death of innocents |publisher=Bantam Books |location=New York |year=1997 |pages= |isbn=0553100130 |oclc= }}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Altman | name-list-format = vanc |title=For Science's Gatekeepers, a Credibility Gap |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/02/health/02docs.htm |quote=Recent disclosures of fraudulent or flawed studies in medical and scientific journals have called into question as never before the merits of their peer-review system. The system is based on journals inviting independent experts to critique submitted manuscripts. The stated aim is to weed out sloppy and bad research, ensuring the integrity of what it has published. |publisher=New York Times |date=May 2, 2006 |access-date=2008-03-26 }}</ref> The case-study upon which Steinschneider's theory was based was later revealed to involve [[Infanticide]] committed by the mother, with Steinschneider allegedly having ignored evidence and reports that the children were being abused.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lucey JF |title=Woman Confesses in Deaths of Children |journal=[[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]] |volume=93 |issue=6 |page=944 |date=June 1994 |pmid= |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/93/6/944-b}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = How Two Baby Deaths Led to a Misguided SIDS Theory | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1997/oct/20/health/he-44680|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1997-10-20|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> In 1997 the editor of [[Pediatrics (journal)]], Jerold Lucey, stated that Steinschneider's original paper on the subject was "seriously flawed" and should not have been published.<ref>{{cite web | title = Setting The Medical Record Straight | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-09-27/news/9709270164_1_sids-cases-dr-alfred-steinschneider-dr-jerold-lucey|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=1997-09-27|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[Marc Straus]] (US), former Chief of Oncology and Associate Professor of Medicine at [[Boston University Medical Center]], in 1982 admitted to "serious deficiencies," including the use of false data, in research studies he supervised. He also admitted to using ineligible patients in his studies, administering drug dosages different from those in his plan, and not assuring compliance with rules of informed consent.<ref name=UPI>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/05/21/Dr-Marc-J-Straus-a-cancer-researcher-barred-from/1804390801600/ |title=Dr. Marc J. Straus, a cancer researcher barred from... |date=May 21, 1982 |website=[[UPI]] |access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = The Commission's Report |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/20/us/doctor-admits-filing-false-data-and-is-barred-from-us-support.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1982-05-20|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/21/us/doctor-denies-role-in-fraud.html |title=Doctor Denies Role in Fraud |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=May 21, 2016 |access-date=August 20, 2016}}</ref> * [[Jon Sudbø]] (Norway), an oncologist and former Associate Professor at the [[University of Oslo]], was found in a 2006 investigation to have manipulated and fabricated data in grant applications and 15 of his research papers.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/02/health/02docs.htm | work=The New York Times | first1=Lawrence K. | last1=Altman | name-list-format = vanc | title=For Science's Gatekeepers, a Credibility Gap | date=2006-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = The Commission's Report | url = http://www.rikshospitalet.no:80/content/res_bibl/6633.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060920200752/http://www.rikshospitalet.no/content/res_bibl/6633.pdf | archive-date = 2006-09-20 | dead-url = yes | publisher = Rikshospitalet | date = 2006-06-30 | access-date = 2018-03-29 | df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Case Summary: Sudbo, Jon | url = https://ori.hhs.gov/content/case-summary-sudbo-jon|publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services Office of Research Integrity|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Sudbø has had 12 of his publications retracted.<ref name="leaderboard"/> * Akio Sugino (Japan), a former molecular biologist and professor at [[Osaka University]], was dismissed from the University following an investigation that revealed he fabricated research data in two of his papers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Normile D | title = Scientific misconduct. Japan's universities take action | journal = Science | volume = 315 | issue = 5808 | page = 26 | date = January 2007 | pmid = 17204614 | doi = 10.1126/science.315.5808.26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/445240a|title=Misconduct? It's all academic|publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited|date=2007-01-17|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Sophie L. | last = Rovner | name-list-format = vanc | title = Research Ethics: Experts ponder how best to prevent and respond to scientific misconduct as three Japanese cases conclude |url=http://pubs.acs.org/email/cen/html/021207094654.html|publisher=American Chemical Society|date=2007-02-12|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[William Summerlin]] (US), a dermatologist formerly at [[Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center]], in 1974 committed scientific misconduct in his work on transplant immunology.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lafollette MC | title = The evolution of the "scientific misconduct" issue: An historical overview | journal = Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine. Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine | volume = 224 | issue = 4 | pages = 211–15 | date = September 2000 | pmid = 10964254 | doi = 10.1111/j.1525-1373.2000.22423.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Jane E. | last = Brody | name-list-format = vanc | title = Inquiry at Cancer Center Finds Fraud in Research |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/25/archives/article-5-no-title-fraud-is-charged-at-cancer-center-premature.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1974-05-25|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> It was from this case that the phrase "painting the mice" originated as a synonym for research fraud.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,879645,00.html?iid=chix-sphere Skin Deep], review of ''The Patchwork Mouse'', ''[[Time magazine]]'', March 8, 1976</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.fasebj.org/doi/full/10.1096/fj.06-0401ufm|publisher=Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology|date=2006-04-01|access-date=2018-03-29|doi=10.1096/fj.06-0401ufm|title=Science fraud: From patchwork mouse to patchwork data|journal=The FASEB Journal|volume=20|issue=6|pages=587|last1=Weissmann|first1=Gerald}}</ref> * Kazunari Taira (Japan), formerly of the biochemistry and biotechnology department at the [[University of Tokyo]], was found by a University committee to have faked experiments on RNA interference.<ref name=pmid16598217>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fuyuno I | title = Further accusations rock Japanese RNA laboratory | journal = Nature | volume = 440 | issue = 7085 | pages = 720–21 | date = April 2006 | pmid = 16598217 | doi = 10.1038/440720a }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fuyuno I, Cyranoski D | title = Doubts over biochemist's data expose holes in Japanese fraud laws | journal = Nature | volume = 439 | issue = 7076 | pages = 514 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16452938 | doi = 10.1038/439514a }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Ichiko | last = Fuyuno | name-list-format = vanc | title = Scientist faces irreproducible results |url=https://www.nature.com/news/2006/060127/full/news060123-14.html|publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited|date=2006-01-27|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Professor faked enzyme test todai panel | url = https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2006/01/28/national/professor-faked-enzyme-test-todai-panel/#.Wr05pn8h3X4|publisher=The Japan Times Ltd.|date=2006-01-28|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[Andrew Wakefield]] (UK), a former practicing physician and senior lecturer at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in London, was found guilty of dishonesty in his research and banned from medicine by the UK [[General Medical Council]] following an investigation by [[Brian Deer]] of the London [[Sunday Times]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=General Medical Council |date=24 May 2010 |title=Dr. Andrew Jeremy Wakefield: Determination on Serious Professional Misconduct (SPM) and Sanction |access-date=10 August 2011 |url=http://www.gmc-uk.org/Wakefield_SPM_and_SANCTION.pdf_32595267.pdf |format=PDF |deadurl=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809092833/http://www.gmc-uk.org/Wakefield_SPM_and_SANCTION.pdf_32595267.pdf |archive-date=9 August 2011 |df= }}</ref> Wakefield's claims of a link between the [[MMR vaccine]], [[Autism spectrum disorder|autism]] and [[inflammatory bowel disease]] have been reported in the [[British Medical Journal]] as "based not on bad science but on a deliberate fraud,"<ref>{{cite web | title = The fraud behind the MMR scare |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/342/bmj.d22|publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2011-01-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> and the 1998 paper originally presenting his theory was retracted in 2010 by ''The Lancet''.<ref>{{cite web | title = RETRACTED: Ileal-lymphoid-nodular hyperplasia, non-specific colitis, and pervasive developmental disorder in children | url = http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2897%2911096-0/abstract|publisher=Elsevier Limited|date=2010-02-02|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Lancet retracts Wakefield’s MMR paper | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/340/bmj.c696 | publisher = BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2010-02-02|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> Wakefield was unsuccessful in an attempt to sue detractors/critics for libel and defamation.<ref>{{cite web | title = Wakefield Libel Suit Rejected | url = https://www.medpagetoday.com/publichealthpolicy/ethics/34071 |publisher=MedPage Today LLC|date=2012-08-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Texas judge throws out Wakefield’s libel action against BMJ | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/345/bmj.e5328 | publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2012-08-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> * Weishui Y. Weiser (US), a former Assistant Professor of Medicine at [[Harvard Medical School]], falsified data supported by two [[Public Health Service]] (PHS) grants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/not95-262.html |title=Nih Guide: Findings Of Scientific Misconduct |publisher=Grants.nih.gov |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pravda |first=Douglas M. | name-list-format = vanc |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1995/12/12/nih-cites-two-researchers-for-misconduct/ |title=NIH Cites Two Researchers For Misconduct &#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=Thecrimson.com |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> Weiser has had at least four publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = ORI findings lead to two retractions — nearly 17 years later | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2012/09/10/ori-findings-lead-to-two-retractions-nearly-17-years-later/ | publisher = Retraction Watch|date=2012-09-10|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> * [[Industrial Bio-Test Laboratories]] fabricated research data to the extent that upon FDA analysis of 867 studies, 618 (71%) were deemed invalid, including many of which were used to gain regulatory approval for widely used household and industrial products.<ref name='JDC essay'>{{cite web | url = http://www.westgard.com/guest16.htm | title = Good Laboratory Practice versus CLIA | access-date = 2012-07-12 | last = Cook | first = Janine Denis | work = University of Maryland, Baltimore}}</ref><ref name='Schneider 1983-05-11 (b)'>{{cite news | first = Keith | last = Schneider | name-list-format = vanc | title = IBT Labs' trial reveals faked data | date = 1983-05-11 | url = http://www.unz.org/Pub/InTheseTimes-1983may11-00003 | work = In These Times | pages = 3, 6 | access-date = 2012-07-16}}</ref> * Researchers at [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]] retracted a 2012 paper published in ''[[Surgery]]'' in 2016 after an internal investigation determined that an image used in the paper was fabricated. The investigation was sparked by other scientists who questioned the paper’s claim to have presented the molecular underpinnings of how a form of [[curcumin]] could reduce the growth of [[neuroblastoma]].<ref>{{cite web | title =St. Jude investigation finds faked data in brain tumor paper|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/11/09/investigation-at-st-jude-finds-faked-data-in-surgery-paper/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-11-09|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref> The official retraction stated, “The irregularities in Figure 3E have been investigated by the co-authors and [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]], and the investigation concluded that the image was fabricated. We therefore retract the publication.”<ref>{{cite web | title =Retraction notice to "Liposome-encapsulated curcumin suppresses neuroblastoma growth through nuclear factor-κB inhibition"|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0039606015009034/|publisher=Surgery|date=February 2016|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>
== Chemistry ==
* Claudio Airoldi (Brazil), former professor at the [[University of Campinas]], and Denis de Jesus Lima Guerra (Brazil), former professor at the [[Federal University of Mato Grosso]], have had 13 of their papers retracted<ref>{{cite web | title = Researcher in Brazil earns 12th retraction for recycling text and figures |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2016/08/16/researcher-in-brazil-earns-12th-retraction-for-recycling-text-and-figures/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-08-16|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> in what was reported as the biggest case of scientific fraud in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Autor da maior fraude científica do Brasil é exonerado da UFMT|url=http://www.olhardireto.com.br/noticias/exibir.asp?id=358847}}</ref> * [[Henk Buck]] (Netherlands), former professor of Physical Organic Chemistry and Organic Chemistry at the [[Eindhoven University of Technology]], was directly involved in The Buck-Goudsmit controversy, in which a potential method to inhibit [[HIV-1]] replication was ultimately shown to be based on flawed research.<ref name="Science Retraction">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moody HM, Quaedflieg PJ, Koole LH, van Genderen MH, Buck HM, Smit L, Jurriaans S, Geelen JL, Goudsmit J | title = Inhibition of HIV-1 infectivity by phosphate-methylated DNA: retraction | journal = Science | volume = 250 | issue = 4977 | pages = 125–26 | date = October 1990 | pmid = 2218505 | doi = 10.1126/science.2218505 }}</ref><ref name="pmid2218505">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moody HM, Quaedflieg PJ, Koole LH, van Genderen MH, Buck HM, Smit L, Jurriaans S, Geelen JL, Goudsmit J | title = Inhibition of HIV-1 infectivity by phosphate-methylated DNA: retraction | journal = Science | volume = 250 | issue = 4977 | pages = 125–6 | date = October 1990 | pmid = 2218505 | doi = | url = http://science.sciencemag.org/content/sci/250/4977/125.full.pdf }}</ref> * Juan Carlos Mejuto (Spain) and Gonzalo Astray Dopazo (Spain) of the [[University of Vigo]] had two papers retracted in 2011 because "significant portions" of the papers duplicated previously published work.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alicia |last=Rivera |title=Ciencia china 'duplicada' en Galicia |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/Ciencia/china/duplicada/Galicia/elpepisoc/20110520elpepisoc_8/Tes | publisher=El País | date=May 20, 2011 }}{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Ingendaay |title=War die Guttenberg-Affäre denn zu gar nichts gut?|url=http://www.faz.net/IN/INtemplates/faznet/default.asp?tpl=common/zwischenseite.asp&dx1={B43A6DE1-AB1B-0749-EF51-A4D52091788B}|publisher= Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung |date=June 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Addition/Correction: Prediction of Refractive Index of Polymers Using Artificial Neural Networks |volume=56 |page=688 |date=2010-02-09 |journal= Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data |doi=10.1021/je200071p |issue=3|last1=Astray |first1=G |last2=Cid |first2=A |last3=Moldes |first3=O |last4=Ferreiro-Lage |first4=J. A |last5=GáLvez |first5=J. F |last6=Mejuto |first6=J. C }}{{Cite journal |title=Addition/Correction: Prediction of Prop-2-enoate Polymer and Styrene Polymer Glass Transition Using Artificial Neural Networks |volume=56 |page=689 |date=2010-02-09 |journal= Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data |doi=10.1021/je200072e |issue=3|last1=Astray |first1=G |last2=Cid |first2=A |last3=Ferreiro-Lage |first3=J. A |last4=GáLvez |first4=J. F |last5=Mejuto |first5=J. C |last6=Nieto-Faza |first6=O }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Something rotten in the state of Spain, say whistleblowers|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/something-rotten-in-the-state-of-spain-say-whistleblowers/420782.article|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=2018-08-09|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Leo Paquette#Scientific misconduct|Leo Paquette]] (US), an Ohio State University professor, plagiarized sections from an unfunded NIH grant application for use in his own NIH grant application.<ref name="NIH">{{Citation | title = Final Findings of Scientific Misconduct | author = Office of Research Integrity | date = June 25, 1993 | publisher= DHHS | periodical = Nih Guide | volume = 22 | issue = 23 | url = https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/not93-177.html | access-date = October 3, 2016 }}</ref> He also plagiarized a NSF proposal for use in one of his scientific publications.<ref name="C&EN-Misconduct">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zurer P | title = NSF, Paquette Settle Misconduct Case | journal = Chemical & Engineering News |volume = 76 | issue = 10 | pages = 25–26 | date = March 9, 1998 | doi= 10.1021/cen-v076n010.p025 }}</ref><ref name="OSU">{{Citation | title = Scientific Misconduct Charge Ruled Valid | last = Gerstner | first = Ruth | date = August 9, 1993 | publisher= Ohio State University | url = https://news.osu.edu/news/1993/08/09/93-08-09_Scientific_Misconduct_Charge_Ruled_Valid/ | access-date = October 3, 2016 }}</ref> * H. Zhong, T. Liu, and their colleagues (China) at [[Jinggangshan University]] have retracted at least 70 papers published in [[Acta Crystallographica]]<ref name="pmid21579903">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhong H, Duan SH, Hong YP, Li ML, Liu YQ, Luo CJ, Luo QY, Xiao SZ, Xie HL, Xu YP, Yang XM, Zeng XR, Zhong QY | title = Retraction of articles by H. Zhong et al | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section E | volume = 66 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = e11–2 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 21579903 | pmc = 2980006 | doi = 10.1107/S1600536809049964 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Retraction of articles by T. Liu et al. | url = https://journals.iucr.org/e/issues/2010/01/00/me0405/index.html|publisher=International Union of Crystallography|date=2010-01-01|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> following analyses that revealed the organic structures claimed in these papers to be impossible or implausible; the supporting data appeared to have been taken from valid structures that had then been altered by substituting atoms.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Harrison WT, Simpson J, Weil M | title = Editorial | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section E | volume = 66 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = e1–2 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 21579902 | pmc = 2980207 | doi = 10.1107/S1600536809051757 | url = http://journals.iucr.org/e/issues/2010/01/00/me0406/ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/8448731.stm |title=Lancet urges China to tackle scientific fraud |author=Doreen Walton |publisher=BBC |date=8 January 2010}}</ref> * Guido Zadel (Germany), published an article with the title "Enantioselective Reactions in a Static Magnetic Field" in 1994.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zadel |first1=Guido |last2=Eisenbraun |first2=Catia |last3=Wolff |first3=Gerd-Joachim |last4=Breitmaier |first4=Eberhard |title=Enantioselective Reactions in a Static Magnetic Field |journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition in English |date=3 March 1994 |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=454–456 |doi=10.1002/anie.199404541}}</ref> His experiments had been manipulated, which led to the retraction of the respective paper and the final loss of his doctoral degree in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bonner Chemiker verliert Doktortitel |url=https://idw-online.de/en/news76031 |website=idw-online.de |language=de}}</ref> The German version of the article is still accessible at Angew. Chem. in 2018 for $59 without any obvious retraction note.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zadel |first1=Guido |last2=Eisenbraun |first2=Catja |last3=Wolff |first3=Gerd-Joachim |last4=Breitmaier |first4=Eberhard |title=Enantioselektive Reaktionen im statischen Magnetfeld |journal=Angewandte Chemie |date=18 February 1994 |volume=106 |issue=4 |pages=460–463 |doi=10.1002/ange.19941060417}}</ref>
== Computer science and mathematics ==* [[Ioan Mang]] (Romania), a computer scientist at the [[University of Oradea]], ublisher=Cs.technion.ac.il |date=2012-05-10 |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the Computer Science Department of [[Technion]], [[Haifa]], [[Israel]]. He was accused of extensive plagiarism in at least eight of his academic papers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Abbott A | title = Romanian scientists fight plagiarism | journal = Nature | volume = 488 | issue = 7411 | pages = 264–65 | date = August 2012 | pmid = 22895311 | doi = 10.1038/488264a }}</ref><ref>[http://iscience.in/blogs/3775/1007/attitudes-towards-plagiarism Attitudes towards plagiarism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728215558/http://iscience.in/blogs/3775/1007/attitudes-towards-plagiarism |date=2013-07-28 }} ''ScienceIn''</ref><ref>[http://www.livescience.com/21023-romanian-prime-minister-plagiarism.html Romanian Prime Minister Accused of Plagiarism] ''Live Science''</ref><ref>[http://www.ithenticate.com/plagiarism-checker-blog/bid/83694/Romanian-Education-and-Research-Minister-Accused-of-Plagiarism Romanian Education and Research Minister Accused of Plagiarism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625193009/http://www.ithenticate.com/plagiarism-checker-blog/bid/83694/Romanian-Education-and-Research-Minister-Accused-of-Plagiarism |date=2012-06-25 }} ''iThenticate''</ref> * [[Dănuț Marcu]] (Romania), a mathematician and computer scientist, was banned from publishing in several journals due to plagiarism.<ref>{{citation|title=Plagiarism in Academia|first=Syed|last=Shahabuddin|url=http://www.isetl.org/ijtlhe/pdf/IJTLHE641.pdf|journal=International Journal of Teaching and Learning in Higher Education|volume=21|year=2009|issue=3|pages=353–59}}. This paper quotes {{harvtxt|Boussou|Martello|Plastria|2006}} concerning Marcu, including the quote from an unnamed "well-known mathematician" that "Marcu is a notorious plagiarist".</ref> He had submitted a manuscript for publication that was a word-for-word replicate of a published paper written by another author.<ref>Karl Strambach and Ferdinand D. Veldkamp, "[http://www.springerlink.com/content/k7rm674498665241/ Editorial statement]", ''Geometriae Dedicata'' '''32''' (1989), p. 253; see also {{Zbl|0701.51004}} and {{MR|1038400}}.</ref>
== Physics == * Teruji Cho (Japan), a researcher of [[plasma physics]], was dismissed from the [[University of Tsukuba]] following his falsification of raw data in a research paper.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigation Report on the Suspected Scientific Misconduct |url=http://www.tsukuba.ac.jp/english/public/pressrelease/p_report/report_d.pdf |format=PDF |date=2007-11-27 |author=University of Tsukuba |access-date=2010-05-05}}{{Cite journal |title=University of Tsukuba defends professor's dismissal |author=Hiroshi Mizubayashi |journal=Physics Today |doi= 10.1063/1.3086082 |volume=62 |issue=2 |pages=12–14|year=2009 }}</ref> * Akihisa Inoue (Japan), [[metallurgist]] and former President of [[Tohoku University]], has retracted seven papers for duplication.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Japan fails to settle University dispute | journal = Nature | volume = 483 | issue = 7389 | page = 259 | date = March 2012 | pmid = 22422240 | doi = 10.1038/483259a }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Faculty members in conflict with president of Japanese university | journal = Nature | volume = 470 | issue = 7335 | pages = 446–47 | date = February 2011 | pmid = 21350457 | doi = 10.1038/470446a }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/496005a |title=A record made to be broken |journal=Nature |volume=496 |issue=7443 |page=5 |year=2013 }}</ref> * [[Victor Ninov]] (US), a nuclear chemist formerly at [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]], was dismissed from his position after falsifying his work on element discovery.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/15/science/at-lawrence-berkeley-physicists-say-a-colleague-took-them-for-a-ride.html?scp=2&sq=victor%20ninov&st=cse&pagewanted=1 At Lawrence Berkeley, Physicists Say a Colleague Took Them for a Ride] George Johnson, The New York Times, 15 October 2002</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elements 116 and 118 Were a Sham|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2002/07/elements-116-and-118-were-sham|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|date=2002-07-15|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> * [[Schön scandal|Jan Hendrik Schön]] (Germany, US), a researcher in the physics of [[semiconductors]] formerly employed by [[Bell Labs]], forged results by using the same data sets for different and unrelated experiments.<ref name="DeutscheWelle">{{cite news |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |title=Scandal Rocks Scientific Community |date=30 September 2002 |url=http://www.deutsche-welle.de/dw/article/0,2144,646321,00.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Report of the Investigation Committee on the Possibility of Scientific Misconduct in the Work of Hendrik Schön And coauthors | url = https://media-bell-labs-com.s3.amazonaws.com/pages/20170403_1709/misconduct-revew-report-lucent.pdf |publisher=Lucent Technologies |date=September 2002|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> Schön has had 32 of his publications retracted.<ref name="leaderboard"/> * Alexander Spivak (Israel), a tenured senior lecturer at [[Holon Institute of Technology]] (HIT), twice plagiarized a paper<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1137/S0036139900372363 |title=The Stationary Arrival Process of Independent Diffusers from a Continuum to an Absorbing Boundary is Poissonian |journal=SIAM Journal on Applied Mathematics |volume=62 |issue=2 |page=433 |year=2001 |last1=Nadler |first1=B |last2=Naeh |first2=T |last3=Schuss |first3=Z }}</ref> written by his former postdoctoral adviser and two other researchers from [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://ijpam.eu/contents/2008-44-3/2/ |title=The Steady State Absorption Stream at an Absorbing Boundary |author=A. Spivak (2008) |volume=44 |pages=327–33 |journal=International Journal of Pure and Applied Mathematics}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://ijpam.eu/contents/2008-48-2/9/ |title=The Probabilistic Characterization of the Arrival Process of Particles into an Absorbing Boundary |author=A. Spivak (2008) |volume=48 |pages=73–79 |journal=International Journal of Pure and Applied Mathematics}}</ref> The HIT administration's handling of Spivak's misconduct received harsh criticism in Israel<ref>{{cite news |title=Lies of Educators |author=Tali Heruti-Sover |url=http://blogs.haaretz.co.il/taliherutisover/2124/ |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |date=2014-09-03}}</ref> and abroad.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferguson|first=Cat|title=Blatant plagiarism sinks paper (and earns a sabbatical!) for mathematician|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2014/10/07/blatant-plagiarism-sinks-paper-and-earns-a-sabbatical-for-mathematician/|work=Retraction Watch}}</ref> In May 2015, another paper by Spivak was retracted for duplication.<ref>{{Cite conference |url=http://lib.amcl.tuc.gr/handle/triton/73 |title=Successive approximations for optimal control in some nonlinear systems with small parameter (RETRACTED Article)|author=A. Spivak (2014) | pages=256–59 |booktitle=Proceedings of the 6th International Conference on Numerical Analysis |isbn= 978-9608475229}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Katsnelson|first=Alla|title=Duplication of "a major part of text and results" adds up to third retraction for mathematician |url=http://retractionwatch.com/2015/06/23/duplication-of-a-major-part-of-text-and-results-adds-up-to-third-retraction-for-mathematician/|work=Retraction Watch}}</ref> * [[Rusi Taleyarkhan]] (US), a nuclear engineer at [[Purdue University]], was found by a University committee in 2008 to have falsified his research.<ref name="latimes">[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-sci-misconduct19-2008jul19,0,1765099.story Purdue physicist found guilty of misconduct], Los Angeles Times, July 19, 2008, Thomas H. Maugh II</ref>
== Plant biology == * Supachai Lorlowhakarn (Thailand), an official at Thailand’s National Innovation Agency (NIA), plagiarized 80% of his PhD thesis concerning asparagus cultivation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20120818084937660|title=Plagiarism controversy raises questions over academic integrity|website=www.universityworldnews.com|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> Lorlowhakarn was in 2012 found guilty of criminal forgery, had his PhD degree retracted, was fined, and received a six-month suspended jail sentence, but was not dismissed from NIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20120825150255758|title=Plagiarism scandal continues after forgery verdict |website=www.universityworldnews.com|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> The [[whistleblower]] (and plagiarized author) in this case, [[United Nations]] official Wyn Ellis, was in 2015 detained by Thai immigration officials for four days, apparently due to an official letter from Lorlowhakarn characterizing Ellis as a "danger to Thai society."<ref>{{cite web|title=Whistleblower released after being held for 4 days in Bangkok airport|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/09/08/whistleblower-released-after-being-held-for-4-days-in-bangkok-airport/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-09-08|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Olivier Voinnet]] (France) was suspended in 2015 for two years from the [[CNRS]] (the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research]]) due to multiple cases of data manipulation.<ref name="cnrs_investigation">{{cite web|url=http://www2.cnrs.fr/en/2593.htm|title=Completion of the procedure against Olivier Voinnet|author=Press release|work=cnrs.fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=(Voinnet%20O%5BAuthor%5D)%20AND%20%22retracted%20publication%22%5BPublication%20Type%5D|title=PubMed search; Voinnet and retractions}}</ref> In 2016 [[EMBO]] recalled the Gold Medal awarded to Voinnet in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2016/01/28/embo-takes-back-voinnets-award-investigates-other-awardee-who-just-lost-a-nature-genetics-paper/|title=EMBO takes back Voinnet's award, investigates other awardee who just lost a Nature Genetics paper|work=retractionwatch.com|deadurl=yes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315083319/http://retractionwatch.com/2016/01/28/embo-takes-back-voinnets-award-investigates-other-awardee-who-just-lost-a-nature-genetics-paper/|archive-date=2016-03-15|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/45183/title/Funding-Ban-for-Plant-Biologist/|title=Funding Ban for Plant Biologist|work=the-scientist.com}}</ref> Voinnet has had eight research publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Caught Our Notice: Voinnet co-author issues another correction |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/16/caught-our-notice-voinnet-co-author-issues-another-correction/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-16|access-date=2018-03-20}}</ref>
== Social sciences == * [[Mart Bax]] (Netherlands), former professor of political anthropology at the [[Vrije Universiteit]], committed multiple acts of scientific misconduct including data fabrication.<ref>[http://www.vu.nl/nl/nieuws-agenda/nieuws/2013/apr-jun/commissie-baud-onderzoekt-beschuldiging-wetenschapsfraude.asp "Commissie-Baud onderzoekt beschuldiging wetenschapsfraude"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. VU nieuws, April 29, 2013.</ref><ref>Michiel Baud, Susan Legêne, and Peter Pels (September 9, 2013). [http://www.vu.nl/nl/Images/20130910_RapportBax_tcm9-356928.pdf "Draaien om de werkelijkheid: Rapport over het antropologisch werk van prof. em. M.M.G. Bax"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928122206/http://www.vu.nl/nl/Images/20130910_RapportBax_tcm9-356928.pdf |date=2013-09-28 }}.</ref><ref>[http://www.vu.nl/nl/nieuws-agenda/nieuws/2013/jul-sep/College-van-Bestuur-VU-onderschrijft-conclusies-onderzoekscommissie-Baud.asp "College van Bestuur VU onderschrijft conclusies onderzoekscommissie Baud"]. VU nieuws, September 23, 2013.</ref> Bax, who has had two of his publications retracted, was found in 2013 to have never published 61 of the papers he listed on his CV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second retraction appears for Mart Bax|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2014/12/29/second-retraction-appears-mart-bax/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2014-12-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch anthropologist Mart Bax faked 61 papers, says university|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2013/09/23/dutch-anthropologist-mart-bax-faked-61-papers-says-university/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-09-23|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Ward Churchill]] (US), former professor of ethnic studies at [[University of Colorado]], was accused by a University committee of multiple counts of plagiarism, fabrication, and falsification.<ref name="misconduct_report">{{Cite journal | title = Report On Professor Ward Churchill Presented To Media | first1 = Marianne | last1 = Wesson | first2 = Robert | last2 = Clinton | first3 = José | last3 = Limón | first4 = Marjorie | last4 = McIntosh | first5 = Michael | last5 = Radelet | date = May 15, 2006 | publisher = University of Colorado at Boulder | url = https://www.colorado.edu/today/2006/05/15/report-professor-ward-churchill-presented-media | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title =Churchill Verdict Rendered | work = colorado.edu | url =https://www.colorado.edu/coloradan/2009/06/01/churchill-verdict-rendered | access-date=2018-07-30 }}</ref> After the University Chancellor recommended Churchill's dismissal to the Board of Regents, Churchill was in 2009 deemed by a jury to have been wrongly fired, although the presiding judge declined to reinstate him.<ref name="wrongly fired">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/us/03churchill.html?hp&_r=0 Jury Says Professor Was Wrongly Fired]; ''New York Times''; Kirk Johnson and Katherine Q. Seelye; April 2, 2009</ref> In 2010 the Colorado State Court of Appeals upheld the judge's decision to not reinstate Churchill, a decision that in 2012 was upheld by the Colorado Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fired Colorado professor Ward Churchill loses Supreme Court appeal|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2012/09/10/fired-colorado-professor-ward-churchill-loses-supreme-court-appeal/|author=Cotton, Anthony|publisher=Digital First Media|date=2012-09-10|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> In 2013 the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] declined to hear Churchill's appeal of the Colorado Supreme Court decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Loss for Ward Churchill|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2013/04/02/supreme-court-rejects-appeal-ward-churchill|author=Jaschik, Scott|publisher=Inside Higher Ed|date=2013-04-02|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> * Jens Förster (Netherlands, Germany), a social psychologist formerly of the [[University of Amsterdam]] and the [[Ruhr-Universität Bochum]], fabricated data reported in a number of published papers. An investigating committee in 2015 identified in Förster's work data that were "practically impossible" and displayed "strong evidence for low veracity."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aab2519 |title=Social psychologist relinquishes chair after data manipulation charges |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Van Kolfschooten |first1=Frank }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aac6776 |title=Report further incriminates social psychologist Jens Förster |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Van Kolfschooten |first1=Frank }}</ref> Förster has had three of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Journal adds concern notice to paper by psychologist Jens Förster|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/09/29/journal-adds-concern-notice-paper-psychologist-jens-forster//|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-09-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=University requests 4th retraction for psychologist under fire|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/12/15/university-requests-4th-retraction-psychologist-fire/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-12-15|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Bruno Frey]] (Switzerland), an economist formerly at the [[University of Zurich]], in 2010-11 committed multiple acts of [[self-plagiarism]] in articles about the [[Titanic disaster|''Titanic'' disaster]]. Frey admitted to the self-plagiarism, terming the acts "grave mistake[s]" and "deplorable."<ref name="WSJ">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/ideas-market/2011/07/13/economist-slammed-for-concurrent-publications/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Christopher | last=Shea | title=Economist Slammed for ‘Concurrent Publications' | date=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref name="AEAweb">{{cite journal |doi=10.1257/jep.25.3.239 |title=Correspondence |journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives |volume=25 |issue=3 |page=239 |year=2011 }}</ref> * [[Michael LaCour]] (US), former graduate student in political science at [[UCLA]], was the lead author of the 2014 article [[When contact changes minds]]. Published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' and making international headlines, the paper was later retracted because of numerous irregularities in the methodology and falsified data.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stanford.edu/~dbroock/broockman_kalla_aronow_lg_irregularities.pdf | title=Irregularities in LaCour (2014) | date=19 May 2015 | access-date=30 May 2015 | author=Broockman, David, Kalla, Joshua, and Aronow, Peter}}</ref><ref>http://retractionwatch.com/2015/06/18/if-you-think-its-rude-to-ask-to-look-at-your-co-authors-data-youre-not-doing-science-guest-post/</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/science/journal-science-retracts-study-on-gay-canvassers-and-same-sex-marriage.html | title=Journal Retracts Study on Changing Attitudes on Same-Sex Marriage | work=New York Times | date=28 May 2015 | access-date=28 May 2015 | author=Carey, Benedict}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aac4659 |title=Science retracts gay marriage paper without agreement of lead author La ''Cour'' |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Bohannon |first1=John }}</ref> Following the retraction [[Princeton University]] rescinded an assistant professorship that had been offered to LaCour.<ref>{{cite web|title=U. revokes hire offer after allegations of publishing falsified data|url=http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/article/2015/06/u-revokes-hire-offer-after-allegations-of-publishing-falsified-data/|publisher=The Daily Princetonian|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * Elisabeth Nixon (US), a former student at [[Ohio State University]], had her PhD in anthropology revoked due to plagiarism.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2010/08/26/29882.htm | title=AProfessor Says Another Prof Plagiarized | work=Courthouse News | date=August 26, 2010 | access-date=May 1, 2014 | author=Koeninger, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2010/09/15/plagiarism-a-persistent-problem-on-campuses.html | title= Plagiarism a persistent problem on campuses | work=Columbus Dispatch | date=September 15, 2010 | access-date=May 1, 2014 | author=Pyle, Encarnacion}}</ref> * Karen M. Ruggiero (US), former Assistant Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]], fabricated NIH-sponsored research data on gender and discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-02-020.html |title=Nih Guide: Findings Of Scientific Misconduct |publisher=[[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] |date=2001-12-13 |quote=Notice: NOT-OD-02-020 |access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.apa.org/monitor/feb02/fraud.html |title=Research fraud needn't happen at all |author=Bridget Murray |journal=Monitor on Psychology |publisher=[[American Psychological Association]] |volume=33 |issue=2 |date = February 2002|access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/~scifraud/data/sci_fraud_4555.html |title=\Jacobson, Jennifer. "A Psychology Professor Resigns Amid Accusations of Research Fraud at |publisher=Albany.edu |date=2001-08-10 |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> * [[Diederik Stapel]] (Netherlands), former professor of social psychology at [[Tilburg University]], fabricated data in dozens of studies on human behaviour,<ref>{{cite news |author=Gretchen Vogel |title=Dutch 'Lord of the Data' Forged Dozens of Studies |magazine=[[Science (magazine)|Science]] |url=http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/10/report-dutch-lord-of-the-data-fo.html?ref=hp |date=31 October 2011 |access-date=2 November 2011 |deadurl=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103090859/http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/10/report-dutch-lord-of-the-data-fo.html?ref=hp |archive-date=3 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> a deception described by the [[New York Times]] as "an audacious academic fraud."<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/28/magazine/diederik-stapels-audacious-academic-fraud.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1&&pagewanted=all The Mind of a Con Man: Diederik Stapel, a Dutch social psychologist, perpetrated an audacious academic fraud by making up studies that told the world what it wanted to hear about human nature.], NY Times, published April 26, 2013.</ref> Stapel has had 58 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Diederik Stapel now has 58 retractions|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/12/08/diederik-stapel-now-has-58-retractions/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-12-08|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Brian Wansink]] (US), former John S. Dyson Endowed Chair in the Applied Economics and Management Department at [[Cornell University]], was found in 2018 by a University investigatory committee to have "committed academic misconduct in his research and scholarship, including misreporting of research data, problematic statistical techniques, failure to properly document and preserve research results, and inappropriate authorship."<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornell finds that food marketing researcher Brian Wansink committed misconduct, as he announces retirement|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/20/beleaguered-food-marketing-researcher-brian-wansink-announces-his-retirement-from-cornell/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-20|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Prominent Researcher on Eating Habits Resigned After a Scandal Over His Studies|url=http://time.com/5402927/brian-wansink-cornell-resigned/|publisher=Time Inc.|date=2018-09-21|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=This Ivy League food scientist was a media darling. He just submitted his resignation, the school says.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2018/09/20/this-ivy-league-food-scientist-was-media-darling-now-his-studies-are-being-retracted/?utm_term=.13eb37dc3222|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2018-09-20|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref> Wansink has had 13 of his papers retracted, and at least 15 others have been corrected.<ref>{{cite web|title=JAMA journals retract six papers by food marketing researcher Brian Wansink|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/19/jama-journals-retract-six-papers-by-food-marketing-researcher-brian-wansink/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-19|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>
== Other == * In 2016 the scientific publisher [[Springer Nature]] retracted 58 papers from seven journals, authored mostly by [[Iran]]-based researchers, because the papers showed evidence of authorship manipulation, peer-review manipulation, and/or plagiarism.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature.2016.20916 |title=Publisher pulls 58 articles by Iranian scientists over authorship manipulation |journal=Nature |year=2016 |last1=Callaway |first1=Ewen }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Springer, BMC retracting nearly 60 papers for fake reviews and other issues|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2016/11/01/springer-bmc-retracting-nearly-60-papers-for-fake-reviews-and-other-issues/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-11-01|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> * [[Ohio University]] in 2006 alleged more than three dozen cases of plagiarism in master's degree theses dating back 20 years in its mechanical engineering department.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio College Stung by Plagiarism Charges|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/21/AR2006082100068.html|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2006-08-21|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> A former faculty member involved in the plagiarism cases, Jay S. Gunasekera, was removed from his position as department chair, had his title of "distinguished professor" rescinded,<ref>{{cite web|title='Distinguished' No Longer|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2008/02/22/ohio|publisher=Inside Higher Ed|date=2008-02-22|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> and in 2011 settled a lawsuit he had brought against the University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio University professor Jay Gunasekera settles lawsuit over his role in plagiarism scandal|url=https://www.academicjobs.net/news-1200-Ohio_University_professor_Jay_Gunasekera_settles_lawsuit_over_his_role_in_plagiarism_scandal.html|publisher=Academic Jobs|date=2011-03-09|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Another former faculty member implicated in the plagiarism cases, Bhavin Mehta, in 2012 lost a defamation suit he had brought against the University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mehta v. Ohio Univ., 2012 Ohio 3677|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/2694786/mehta-v-ohio-univ/|publisher=CourtListener|date=2012-03-06|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> * 486 Chinese cancer researchers were found guilty of engaging in a fraudulent peer-review scheme by China’s [[Ministry of Science and Technology]]. The investigation was initiated after the retraction of 107 papers published in [[Tumor Biology]] between 2012 and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peer-Review Fraud Scheme Uncovered in China|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49998/title/Peer-Review-Fraud-Scheme-Uncovered-in-China/|website=The Scientist}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nearly 500 researchers guilty of misconduct, says Chinese gov’t investigation|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/07/31/nearly-500-researchers-guilty-misconduct-says-chinese-govt-investigation/|website=Retraction Watch|date=31 July 2017}}</ref> This is reported to be the most papers retracted from one journal.<ref>{{cite web|title=A new record: Major publisher retracting more than 100 studies from cancer journal over fake peer reviews|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/04/20/new-record-major-publisher-retracting-100-studies-cancer-journal-fake-peer-reviews/|website=Retraction Watch|date=20 April 2017}}</ref>
